    {
      "id": "ITLyjy63UG6isx207hu_B",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 1437.7412186383763,
      "y": 9977.192490409927,
      "width": 1255.890676078465,
      "height": 201.17388272411856,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 1,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 0,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "b6H",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 1025119868,
      "version": 893,
      "versionNonce": 1207832571,
      "isDeleted": true,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1775615024300,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "When the payment service starts, the rate limiter library initializes.\nIt fetches configuration from a central config service, which contains the details (IPs/endpoints) of the Redis cluster nodes (S1, S2, S3).\nThe library then establishes connections to all Redis shards.\n\nWhen a request comes from the user, based on business logic (e.g., using user_id), the system computes a hash of the key and deterministically\nselects a shard using a hashing strategy (e.g., hash(user_id) % N or consistent hashing).\nThis ensures that the same user always maps to the same shard.\n\nThe rate limiter then performs an atomic operation (like INCR with EXPIRE) on Redis to update the request count.\nIf the request is within the allowed limit, it is forwarded to the service; otherwise, it is rejected with a 429 (Too Many Requests) response.",
      "fontSize": 16.093910617929485,
      "fontFamily": 8,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "When the payment service starts, the rate limiter library initializes.\nIt fetches configuration from a central config service, which contains the details (IPs/endpoints) of the Redis cluster nodes (S1, S2, S3).\nThe library then establishes connections to all Redis shards.\n\nWhen a request comes from the user, based on business logic (e.g., using user_id), the system computes a hash of the key and deterministically\nselects a shard using a hashing strategy (e.g., hash(user_id) % N or consistent hashing).\nThis ensures that the same user always maps to the same shard.\n\nThe rate limiter then performs an atomic operation (like INCR with EXPIRE) on Redis to update the request count.\nIf the request is within the allowed limit, it is forwarded to the service; otherwise, it is rejected with a 429 (Too Many Requests) response.",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
