    },
    {
      "id": "ZHI_Ld7lY-k9bK1L_JWx0",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 1354.2095005419953,
      "y": 10422.750906301646,
      "width": 1573,
      "height": 1975,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 1,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 0,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "b6L",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 1206306500,
      "version": 224,
      "versionNonce": 1856794971,
      "isDeleted": true,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1775615032806,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "\n1. Leaky Bucket\n\nIdea\n- Requests are added to a queue (bucket)\n- Processed at a fixed rate\n\nBehavior\n- If bucket is full → drop requests\n- Output rate is constant\n\nPros\n- Smooth traffic\n- Prevents sudden spikes\n\nCons\n- Does not allow bursts\n- Can drop valid requests during spikes\n\nOne-liner\nLeaky bucket enforces a constant request processing rate by queuing and dropping overflow.\n\n\n\n2. Fixed Window Counter\n\nIdea\n- Count requests in a fixed time window (e.g., per minute)\n\nBehavior\n- Counter resets after each window\n\nPros\n- Simple to implement\n- Low memory usage\n\nCons\n- Burst problem at window boundary\n  (e.g., 100 requests at end + 100 at start = 200 quickly)\n\nOne-liner\nFixed window counts requests in discrete time intervals but suffers from boundary burst issues.\n\n\n\n3. Sliding Window\n\nIdea\n- Track requests over a moving time window\n\nBehavior\n- More accurate than fixed window\n- Can use:\n         - Sliding log (store timestamps)\n         - Sliding counter (optimized)\n\nPros\n- Prevents burst spikes\n- More accurate rate limiting\n\nCons\n- More complex\n- Higher memory usage\n\nOne-liner\nSliding window limits requests based on a continuously moving time range, giving more accurate control.\n\n\n\nQuick Comparison\n\nAlgorithm            Burst Handling        Accuracy          Complexity\nLeaky Bucket               No                Medium            Medium\nFixed Window               Poor               Low               Low\nSliding Window             Good               High              High\n\n\n\n“I would prefer sliding window for accuracy, but in most real systems, token bucket is used because it balances burst handling and simplicity.”",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 8,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "\n1. Leaky Bucket\n\nIdea\n- Requests are added to a queue (bucket)\n- Processed at a fixed rate\n\nBehavior\n- If bucket is full → drop requests\n- Output rate is constant\n\nPros\n- Smooth traffic\n- Prevents sudden spikes\n\nCons\n- Does not allow bursts\n- Can drop valid requests during spikes\n\nOne-liner\nLeaky bucket enforces a constant request processing rate by queuing and dropping overflow.\n\n\n\n2. Fixed Window Counter\n\nIdea\n- Count requests in a fixed time window (e.g., per minute)\n\nBehavior\n- Counter resets after each window\n\nPros\n- Simple to implement\n- Low memory usage\n\nCons\n- Burst problem at window boundary\n  (e.g., 100 requests at end + 100 at start = 200 quickly)\n\nOne-liner\nFixed window counts requests in discrete time intervals but suffers from boundary burst issues.\n\n\n\n3. Sliding Window\n\nIdea\n- Track requests over a moving time window\n\nBehavior\n- More accurate than fixed window\n- Can use:\n         - Sliding log (store timestamps)\n         - Sliding counter (optimized)\n\nPros\n- Prevents burst spikes\n- More accurate rate limiting\n\nCons\n- More complex\n- Higher memory usage\n\nOne-liner\nSliding window limits requests based on a continuously moving time range, giving more accurate control.\n\n\n\nQuick Comparison\n\nAlgorithm            Burst Handling        Accuracy          Complexity\nLeaky Bucket               No                Medium            Medium\nFixed Window               Poor               Low               Low\nSliding Window             Good               High              High\n\n\n\n“I would prefer sliding window for accuracy, but in most real systems, token bucket is used because it balances burst handling and simplicity.”",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
